## BLOCK 1: SERPENT/DRAGON CIVILIZATIONS IN ASIAN PRIMARY TEXTS (Chinese, Japanese, Korean, Vietnamese, Thai, Khmer)

**Q1.** Chinese (Classical) — The Lóng (龍) tradition in Shan Hai Jing, Huainanzi, Shuowen Jiezi: are dragons described as a SPECIES with civilization, cities, governance? What are the Dragon Kings (龍王) — rulers of underwater kingdoms with courts, armies, treasure? Do they predate humanity in the Chinese cosmological timeline? Do they interbreed with humans — any dynasty or hero with dragon parentage?

**Q2.** Chinese — Fu Xi and Nüwa depicted with serpentine lower bodies in Han Dynasty art. Shan Hai Jing: how many serpent-bodied or serpent-associated beings are catalogued? Are they described as a population/species or individual anomalies? What is their relationship to human civilization — teachers, rulers, predecessors?

**Q3.** Japanese — Ryūjin/Watatsumi (海神) and the Dragon Palace (龍宮城). Kojiki and Nihon Shoki: Toyotama-hime (dragon king's daughter) marries into the imperial line. What does the original text say about her TRUE FORM? How does the imperial dynasty claim biological descent from dragon-beings? Are there other Japanese traditions of serpent/dragon civilization predating humans?

**Q4.** Korean — Yong (용/龍) traditions in Korean-language sources beyond the Samguk Yusa. The Imugi (이무기) — serpent that must wait 1000 years to become a dragon. Dragon King of the East Sea. Any Korean text describing dragon-beings as a pre-human or parallel intelligent species? What do Korean shamanic (무속/Musok) traditions say about serpent spirits?

**Q5.** Southeast Asian — Nāga traditions in Thai (พญานาค/Phaya Nak), Khmer (នាគ/Neak), Lao, and Vietnamese sources. The Mekong Nāga: is this the same being as the Sanskrit Nāga under a different name, or an independent tradition? Khmer foundation myth: Kaundinya marries Nāga princess Soma — the ENTIRE Khmer civilization claims Nāga descent. What do Khmer-language inscriptions say about this?

