## BLOCK 4: THE SOUL AS UNIQUELY HUMAN — WHAT OTHER BEINGS DON'T HAVE (Hebrew, Arabic, Sanskrit, Tibetan)

**Q14.** Hebrew/Aramaic — Do the Talmud and Kabbalah describe angels, Watchers, shedim, or other non-human beings as having SOULS in the same sense humans do? What is the specific difference between human neshamah and angelic existence? Does any text say the Watchers LACK something humans have? What makes human souls unique in the Lurianic framework — is it the connection to Adam's composite soul, or something else?

**Q15.** Arabic — Do jinn have SOULS (rūḥ/nafs) in the Quranic framework? They have free will (Q 72:11 — "among us are righteous and among us are other than that"), they die (Q 55:26-27), they face judgment. But do they carry the divine breath (nafakha) that Adam received (Q 15:29 — "I breathed into him of My spirit")? Is the nafakha unique to humans? What do Arabic commentaries say about what jinn DON'T have that humans DO?

**Q16.** Sanskrit — The ātman doctrine: do Nāgas, Asuras, Devas, Gandharvas, and other non-human beings have ātman? Can they achieve mokṣa? The Bhagavad Gītā says all beings are ātman — but are there LEVELS or TYPES of soul? Does any text distinguish human soul-potential from non-human soul-potential? What makes being born human precious in the Hindu framework?

**Q17.** Tibetan — "Precious human rebirth" (dal 'byor) doctrine. Why is human birth specifically precious — what do gods, animals, hungry ghosts, and hell-beings LACK that humans have? Is it the capacity for RECOGNITION (pratyabhijñā-equivalent)? Do the texts say that even devas in heaven can't achieve liberation — only humans can? What specifically about human existence enables enlightenment?

